          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4" style="color: var(--navy);">The Case for DIY Kitchens</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">DIY Kitchens is a name that sometimes misleads. Despite the brand name, DIY Kitchens does not supply flat-pack kitchens for self-assembly. The company, based in Yorkshire, manufactures and supplies rigid, pre-assembled kitchen carcasses direct to homeowners from its own factory — cutting out the retail middleman and passing the saving on. The result, in my experience after fitting many of their kitchens, is genuinely impressive quality at below-retail prices.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">DIY Kitchens sits in an interesting position: it competes with brands like Wren on quality but with a direct-from-factory model that removes showroom overhead from the pricing. For homeowners who are comfortable designing their kitchen online and managing the buying process without a physical showroom, it is worth understanding how it compares.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Unit Construction and Quality</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">DIY Kitchens supplies rigid, pre-assembled carcasses from its own manufacturing facility. The construction specification — including 18mm carcass sides, solid back panels, and soft-close hinges and drawer runners as standard — competes well with mid-to-premium offerings from Wren. In some cases, the DIY Kitchens specification exceeds what you get at equivalent price points from Wren, because the factory-direct model allows more of the budget to go into the product rather than the retail overhead.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Wren's unit quality varies across its extensive range. Entry-level Wren kitchens are not specified to the same standard as DIY Kitchens at comparable price points. Wren's premium ranges — Infinity Plus and above — are well constructed, but they carry a price premium that reflects both the product and the brand and showroom overhead. When comparing like for like, DIY Kitchens frequently represents better value per unit.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Range and Style Selection</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Wren has a significantly wider range than DIY Kitchens — more than forty door styles, a broader palette of colours, and a greater variety of specialist units and accessories. For homeowners with a very specific aesthetic requirement or an unusual kitchen layout, Wren's breadth may be a genuine advantage.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">DIY Kitchens focuses on a curated range of well-designed, quality-led styles. The range is narrower but the selection within it is considered. The most popular styles — shaker, handleless, painted — are represented with multiple colour and finish options. For the majority of homeowners who are looking for a quality kitchen in one of the mainstream styles, DIY Kitchens' range is more than sufficient.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">The Buying Experience</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Wren operates physical showrooms across the UK. You can visit, see the ranges in person, work with a designer, and make decisions based on tactile experience of the products. For many homeowners, this in-person experience is valuable — seeing how a door colour looks under lighting, touching the handle, pulling a drawer open.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">DIY Kitchens is an online-only business. The design and ordering process is entirely digital, supported by an online planner and a sample-ordering service. For homeowners who are comfortable working online and who have a clear idea of what they want, this is not a limitation. For those who need a guided, in-person design experience, the absence of a showroom is a genuine drawback.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Delivery and Lead Times</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Wren typically offers relatively fast delivery — often within a few weeks of ordering. DIY Kitchens manufactures to order, which can mean slightly longer lead times, though the company has improved its delivery timelines significantly. Check current lead times with both suppliers at the time of ordering, as these change with seasonal demand.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Both supply in rigid pre-assembled format. Both deliver to the home. The practical logistics of the delivery — checking components, storing them before installation, reporting any damage — are similar for both brands.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Installation Experience</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Having fitted DIY Kitchens extensively alongside Wren and other brands, I can confirm that from an installation perspective, both are rigid pre-assembled and install at essentially the same speed. The carcass dimensions, fixing systems, and hardware are all standard and familiar. An experienced fitter will not need any additional time or specialist knowledge to install a DIY Kitchens kitchen compared to a Wren kitchen.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">One practical note: DIY Kitchens' direct supply model means your point of contact for any delivery issues or replacement components is the company's customer service team rather than a local depot. In my experience, their customer service is responsive, but it is worth being aware that replacement parts come via delivery rather than same-day collection from a local branch.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Which Offers Better Value?</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">At equivalent quality specifications, DIY Kitchens frequently offers better value per unit than Wren. The factory-direct model removes retail overhead from the pricing, which means more of your budget goes into the product. If you are comfortable with an online buying experience and do not need a physical showroom, DIY Kitchens is worth serious consideration alongside Wren.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">If you want a guided showroom experience, the widest possible range of styles, or faster confirmed delivery, Wren's model has advantages that the DIY Kitchens direct model cannot match. The right choice depends on how you prefer to buy, not just what you get for the money.</p>
        `,
        takeaways: [
          "DIY Kitchens supplies rigid pre-assembled carcasses direct from its Yorkshire factory, often representing better value per unit than Wren at equivalent specifications.",
          "Wren has a wider range and physical showrooms; DIY Kitchens is online-only with a focused, quality-led range.",
          "Both install at the same speed — both supply rigid pre-assembled carcasses with standard dimensions and fixing systems.",
