        metaDescription: "In-frame vs shaker kitchens compared — construction, installation time, cost, appearance and durability. An honest fitter's guide after 30 years fitting both.",
        answer: "In-frame kitchens have doors hung within a solid timber frame that is part of the carcass structure — a traditional furniture-making technique. Shaker kitchens have doors hung on the face of a standard carcass. In-frame is more expensive, slower to install, and demands greater precision. It produces a heavier, more furniture-like result.",
